{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0b9f4a43-1047-47aa-bc32-c54a8f6fd9a1","content":"Good news — on .NET 10, `dotnet test` uses Microsoft Testing Platform **natively by default**. You no longer need the opt-in property.\n\n**Remove `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport`** — it was the .NET 9 bridge flag. Keep `EnableMSTestRunner`, which is still required to produce the MTP-based test host.\n\nHere's the cleanup:","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_bY2SZACbYGN0KqADt0YhJw","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-d7a3715ed2574cefaa37ad21a9d4aa7e/TestProject.csproj","old_str":"    <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n    <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>","new_str":"    <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"edit the file at /tmp/sv-d7a3715ed2574cefaa37ad21a9d4aa7e/TestProject.csproj."}],"interactionId":"fa8ebcdd-33c0-4077-bf27-8bd8268b616a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is on .NET 10 SDK (10.0.100) and is using MSTest with `EnableMSTestRunner` and `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` set to true. They want to know about .NET 10's native MTP support.\n\nIn .NET 10, `dotnet test` natively uses Microsoft Testing Platform (MTP) as the default test runner. This means:\n\n1. `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` is **no longer needed** — it was a .NET 9 opt-in property to bridge `dotnet test` with MTP. In .NET 10, this is the default behavior.\n\n\n2. `EnableMSTestRunner` is still required — it configures MSTest to generate a self-contained executable that leverages MTP under the hood.\n\nSo they should remove `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` since it's now redundant on .NET 10.","outputTokens":504,"requestId":"2865:2EAA97:16694A3:17CFA88:6A046048"},"id":"e10df4d4-9538-47b3-ada7-edb03661b212","timestamp":"2026-05-13T11:28:21.510Z","parentId":"f91c2583-b131-4f8c-bc0f-cc1a6452c627"}
